==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spun
<hw>Spun</hw> <pr>(sp⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of
<er>Spin</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spun hay</b></col>, <cd>hay twisted into ropes for
convenient carriage, as on a military expedition.</cd> -- <col><b>Spun
silk</b></col>, <cd>a cheap article produced from floss, or
short-fibered, broken, and waste silk, carded and spun, in distinction
from the long filaments wound from the cocoon. It is often mixed with
cotton.</cd> -- <col><b>Spun yarn</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
line formed of two or more rope-yarns loosely twisted.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spunge</ent>⟦br⟧
